    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, I'll look into the circuit breaker implementation. But the weird thing is, even when traffic isn't at its absolute peak, we still get these random spikes of failures for no apparent reason. It's almost like the service just dies for a few seconds and then works perfectly again without any changes to the infrastructure. It feels totally unpredictable. Any idea why it would be so erratic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The erratic nature of these failures, occurring even without peak traffic, strongly suggests a resource exhaustion issue rather than pure load. A common culprit in this scenario is a \"noisy neighbor\" problem where a single long-running process or a specific batch job in the container or VM is consuming excessive CPU or memory, causing the entire instance to become unresponsive or restart unexpectedly. This would explain why the service seems to \"die\" for a few seconds and then spontaneously recovers once that specific process finishes or the resource is released. To investigate further, you should examine the system-level metrics (CPU, RAM, Swap) specifically during those random failure windows to identify if a resource spike occurred before the timeout.",
